refactor(d4): drop legacy articleMeta.dataSource — switch Sources to ACF Repeater

D4 follow-up. The articleMeta.dataSource (text field, semicolon-separated)
was the v1.0 fallback for article sources. The ACF Repeater
sources.sources[].{name,title,date,url} has been live for a while but
[category]/[slug].astro was still parsing dataSource via parseSources()
instead of reading article.sources directly.

Backend has confirmed they're ready to remove the dataSource ACF field
once the front-end stops querying it. This commit removes the front-end
side. Backend can now mark the field disabled / drop it from ACF.

CHANGES (3 files, -18 / +1)

  src/lib/wp-api.ts
    - removed dataSource: string from ArticleDetail interface
    - removed dataSource line from ARTICLE_PAGE_QUERY (no other queries touched)
    - removed dataSource: post.articleMeta?.dataSource || '' from getArticleData

  src/pages/[category]/[slug].astro
    - removed parseSources() helper (12 lines of legacy text-split logic)
    - changed: const sources = parseSources(article.dataSource)
              -> const sources = article.sources

  src/data/mock-data.ts
    - removed dataSource line from mockArticleDetail (was already obsolete)

PRODUCTION IMPACT (verified locally)

  Salesforce article Sources block now uses ACF Repeater data (6 items
  with full name/title/date from the backend), replacing the previous
  semicolon-parsed text field. Visible improvement: each source carries
  a publication date instead of just the publisher name.

VERIFICATION (all green)

  npm run test:phase1                          87/87
  node baseline/verify-animations.mjs           31/31
  node baseline/verify-a11y.mjs                 17/17
  node baseline/verify-bundle.mjs                7/7
  node baseline/verify-related.mjs              72/72
  node baseline/verify-phase23-internal-links.mjs    5/5
  node baseline/verify-faq.mjs                  49/49
  TOTAL                                       268/268

BACKEND HANDOFF

  After CF Pages deploys this commit, the dataSource field is no longer
  in any GraphQL query the front-end emits. Backend can safely:
  1. Mark articleMeta.dataSource ACF field as disabled (recommended first
     step), or
  2. Drop the field entirely + clean up post_meta entries
  Either path will not affect the front-end build.
